Stack allocation: fixed-size values are placed on the stack. Allocation and deallocation are instant (just moving the stack pointer). Local variables, function parameters, and fixed-size types go on the stack.

let x: i32 = 42;           // Stack
let arr: [u8; 100] = [0; 100]; // Stack

Heap allocation: dynamically-sized or long-lived values go on the heap. Allocation uses the system allocator (slower). Deallocation happens when the owner is dropped.

let s = String::from("hello"); // Heap (String data)
let v = vec![1, 2, 3];         // Heap (Vec data)
let b = Box::new(42);          // Heap (explicit boxing)

Key insight: String and Vec have a small struct on the stack (pointer + length + capacity) that points to heap data. When the stack struct is dropped, the heap data is freed.

Performance: stack allocation is nearly free. Avoid unnecessary heap allocations in hot paths. Use references and slices to avoid copying.
